Eliminating the latent reservoir of HIV   UIC Today Skip to main content  n nUIC Logo n n n n UIC Logo  n         t  Today n       t t   Campus News Academics   Research Events Resources Current Student Resources Faculty   Staff Resources Campus Newspaper   Archives Contact Communicating On Campus Sending Announcements   DDDH UIC Social Media Directory  n n  n n  n n  n n  n n Eliminating the latent reservoir of HIV  n t t t tDecember         t t t A new study suggests that a genetic switch that causes latent HIV inside cells to begin to replicate can be manipulated to completely eradicate the virus from the human body The findings  which suggest a cure for HIV may be possible  are reported in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences reported During infection  The Tat gene circuit is a key piece of HIV DNA that controls the HIV gene transcription and activation  When activated  which eventually burst from the cell and infect neighboring cells  HIV specific immune effector cells kill cells infected with HIV  but only when the cells are being used to produce more of the virus  meaning that the Tat gene circuit is switched on  In cells that are latently infected  the Tat gene circuit is off  and the cell goes about its normal business all the while harboring quiescent HIV  we would be able to cause latently infected cells to start producing more virus  and then they can be destroyed by the immune system  the Richard and Loan Hill Professor of Bioengineering in the University of Illinois at Chicago College of Engineering and a lead author of the paper  So far  there are no drugs successfully targeting this circuit People infected with the HIV virus can live relatively normal lives with exceedingly low or even undetectable viral loads thanks to powerful antiretroviral therapies that work to suppress viral replication  But even in people where the virus is undetectable  The HIV virus can hide in cells in an inactivated state This is a dire situation and makes life long antiretroviral therapy the only option for HIV infected patients infected cells out of their latency Techniques developed to reactivate latent HIV  or kill latent cells  or both The Tat gene circuit has a random probability of being active or inactive  and the switch from inactive to active can happen spontaneously infected cells  reactivation of the Tat gene circuit is still a very rare event Liang and his colleagues developed advanced computational algorithms to study the Tat gene circuit under different conditions  and our results suggest new ways of targeting latent cells that may lead to the eradication of the HIV virus from a host  where latent viral particles are locked into latency by permanently blocking activation of the Tat gene circuit  effective therapeutic strategies can be identified that would one day provide a cure for HIV Liang and Youfang Cao of Merck Research Laboratories are the lead authors of the study  Xue Lei from the University of Illinois at Chicago  and Alan S  Perelson and Ruy M  Ribeiro from the Los Alamos National Laboratory are the collaborators and co authors on the paper This research was supported in part by contract DE AC     NA     from the U S  Department of Energy  grants R   CA        R   GM        R   AI       and R   OD       from the National Institutes of Health  and by the Center for Nonlinear Studies at the Los Alamos National Laboratory  n nContact n nSharon Parmet n t t t t t t t             nsparmet uic edu n n n nCategories n nHealth Sciences Colleges  Research  Research Studies  n Contact  nSharon Parmet n t t t t t t t             nsparmet uic edu n Sharon Parmet sparmet uic edu Categories  nHealth Sciences Colleges  Research  Research Studies  Health Sciences Colleges Research Research Studies Topics HIV HIV  n nUIC Logo n n n n UIC Logo  n         t  Today n       t t   Contact uictoday uic edu Social Media Accounts For the Media Experts Guide Advertise in UIC News Submit Announcements Submit an 